    {
      "label": "Confidence Scoring",
      "file_type": "rationale",
      "source_file": "breaking-change-api-spec.md",
      "source_location": "\u00a74, \u00a77, \u00a713, \u00a714",
      "source_url": null,
      "captured_at": null,
      "author": null,
      "contributor": null,
      "rationale": "Every response carries an explicit confidence field distinguishing structurally-verified facts from changelog-inferred ones; it is both an honesty mechanism about coverage limits (e.g. .d.ts diffing misses runtime-only changes) and a trust signal that lets the consuming agent decide how much to rely on each entry.",
      "id": "docs_breaking_change_api_spec_confidence_scoring",
      "community": 0,
      "norm_label": "confidence scoring"
    },
    {
      "label": "Conservative Breaking-Change Detection",
      "file_type": "rationale",
      "source_file": "breaking-change-api-spec.md",
      "source_location": "\u00a713",
      "source_url": null,
      "captured_at": null,
      "author": null,
      "contributor": null,
      "rationale": "Report only changes that are structurally certain rather than anything plausibly breaking \u2014 conservative is almost certainly right because the tool's entire value proposition is trustworthiness; when data is insufficient, return a clean 'insufficient data' response instead of guessing.",
      "id": "docs_breaking_change_api_spec_conservative_detection",
      "community": 0,
      "norm_label": "conservative breaking-change detection"
    },
    {
      "label": "Freemium Pricing Model",
      "file_type": "rationale",
      "source_file": "breaking-change-api-spec.md",
      "source_location": "\u00a710",
      "source_url": null,
      "captured_at": null,
      "author": null,
      "contributor": null,
      "rationale": "Free tier with generous limits and no required key, paid tier for teams/CI pipelines \u2014 same shape as Context7's proven model; friction kills MCP adoption because agents and developers bail on multi-step signup, while CI teams are the segment with real budget.",
      "id": "docs_breaking_change_api_spec_freemium_model",
      "community": 1,
      "norm_label": "freemium pricing model"
    },
    {
      "label": "No-Signup Free Tier",
      "file_type": "rationale",
      "source_file": "breaking-change-api-spec.md",
      "source_location": "\u00a715",
      "source_url": null,
      "captured_at": null,
      "author": null,
      "contributor": null,
      "rationale": "Since the consumer is often an autonomous agent mid-task, any auth flow requiring a human to stop and fetch a key is a hard wall; unauthenticated requests work at a modest rate limit, and a key is only needed for higher volume.",
      "id": "docs_breaking_change_api_spec_no_signup_free_tier",
      "community": 1,
      "norm_label": "no-signup free tier"
    },
    {
      "label": "AWS-Native Architecture Alternative",
      "file_type": "rationale",
      "source_file": "breaking-change-api-spec.md",
      "source_location": "\u00a79a",
      "source_url": null,
      "captured_at": null,
      "author": null,
      "contributor": null,
      "rationale": "API Gateway + Lambda + Aurora Serverless (or DynamoDB) fits the spiky, cache-dominated traffic shape and is cheaper at true-zero traffic, but costs more in setup and operational complexity than the default PaaS plan; only justified by a specific requirement (customer VPC/compliance, existing AWS credits), never as a default. DynamoDB suits the key-lookup access pattern but makes billing/analytics queries awkward \u2014 a real trade-off, not a free upgrade.",
      "id": "docs_breaking_change_api_spec_aws_native_alternative",
      "community": 5,
      "norm_label": "aws-native architecture alternative"
    },
    {
      "label": "PaaS Hosting Plan (Fly/Render/Railway + Neon)",
